\series bold 
Properties of SVT decomposition
\layout Standard

SVT decomposition can be applied to arbitrary (Euclidean) tensors.
 It is useful because:
\newline 
1.
 Tensor equations split into simpler eqs.
\newline 
2.
 Eqs.\SpecialChar ~
for S/V/T components decouple
\newline 
3.
 Often get algebraic eqs.\SpecialChar ~
in Fourier space
\layout Standard


\series bold 
Theorem 1
\series default 
: If 
\begin_inset Formula $A\delta_{ij}+B_{,ij}+C_{i,j}+C_{j,i}+D_{ij}=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C_{i},D_{ij}\rightarrow0$
\end_inset 

 at least as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{x}\right|^{-2}$
\end_inset 

 at infinity, then each of 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C_{i},D_{ij}=0$
\end_inset 

 everywhere.
\newline 
(Not true in spaces with Lorentzian signature!)
\layout Standard


\series bold 
Theorem 2
\series default 
: EOM for perturbations of a tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset 

 in the presence of (several) background tensors will decouple after using
 a complete decomposition of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset 

 with respect to projections on the background tensors and SVT.
 (In our case, the background tensors are 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset 

)
\layout Standard


\series bold 
Lemma
\series default 
: If a linear function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}$
\end_inset 

 is invariant under 3D rotations, it is equal to zero.
