\layout Standard


\series bold 
Perturbations in flat spacetime
\layout Standard

Use ordinary derivative instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla$
\end_inset 


\newline 
Use 3+1/SVT decomposition for 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset 

 (notation from V.
 F.
 Mukhanov, 
\emph on 
Physical Foundations of Cosmology
\emph default 
, chapter 7):
\begin_inset Formula \[
\begin{cases}
h_{00}=2\Phi;\quad h_{0j}=B_{,j}+S_{j};\quad S_{j}{}^{,j}=0\\
h_{ij}=2\Psi\delta_{ij}+2E_{,ij}+F_{i,j}+F_{j,i}+t_{ij}\end{cases}\]

\end_inset 

Gauge transformations: 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mu\nu}\rightarrow h_{\mu\nu}+\delta h_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta h_{\mu\nu}=u_{\mu,\nu}+u_{\nu,\mu}$
\end_inset 

.
 Apply 3+1/SVT to 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mu}$
\end_inset 

: 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mu}\rightarrow\left\{ a;b_{,j}+c_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{j}{}_{,j}=0$
\end_inset 

.
 Now compute:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\delta h_{00} & =2a_{,0};\quad\delta h_{0j}=a_{0,j}+b_{,0j}+c_{j,0};\\
\delta h_{ij} & =2b_{,ij}+c_{i,j}+c_{j,i}\end{align*}

\end_inset 

By the SVT theorem 1, we have
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align*}
\delta\Phi & =\dot{a},\quad\delta B=a+\dot{b},\quad\delta S_{j}=\dot{c}_{j},\\
\delta\Psi & =0,\quad\delta E=b,\quad\delta F_{j}=c_{j},\quad\delta t_{ij}=0\end{align*}

\end_inset 

Hence we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $E=B=0$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{j}=0$
\end_inset 

 (this is called 
\series bold 
longitudinal
\series default 
 or 
\series bold 
Newtonian
\series default 
 
\series bold 
gauge
\series default 
)
\layout Standard

Remarks: 1.
 Scalar parts of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset 

 contribute to scalar parts of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset 

, vector parts of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset 

 to vector parts of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset 

 (cf.\SpecialChar ~
SVT theorem 2)
\newline 
2.
 The source 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset 

 will, in general, change under a gauge transformation as 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}\rightarrow T_{\mu\nu}+\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{u}}T_{\mu\nu}$
\end_inset 

, but in flat space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\mu\nu}=0$
\end_inset 

.
 Will have to take care with FRW background!
