Ansatz for metric perturbations: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}=a^{2}g$
\end_inset 

, so
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu}=a^{2}(t)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1+2\Phi & 0\\
0 & -\delta_{ij}\left(1-2\Phi\right)+t_{ij}\end{array}\right)\]

\end_inset 

Now need to compute the Einstein tensor\SpecialChar ~
of\SpecialChar ~

\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\newline 
Use linear approximation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi,t_{ij}$
\end_inset 

.
 Note: 
\begin_inset Formula $a(t)$
\end_inset 

 is fixed and has 
\emph on 
no
\emph default 
 perturbations! 
\newline 
Use the conformal transformation formula with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{g}=e^{2\Omega}g$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\equiv\ln a(t)$
\end_inset 

:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\tilde{\textrm{Ein}}=\textrm{Ein}+2H_{\Omega}-2\textrm{d}\Omega\otimes\textrm{d}\Omega-(2\square\Omega+\left|\mathbf{w}\right|^{2})g\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}=\hat{g}^{-1}\textrm{d}\Omega$
\end_inset 

.
 Need the Hessian: 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{\Omega}(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{.}}\nabla_{\mathbf{.}}\Omega\right)(\mathbf{x},\mathbf{y})=\left(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\textrm{d}\Omega\right)(\mathbf{y})=g(\nabla_{\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{w},\mathbf{y})$
\end_inset 

.
 
\newline 

\series bold 
Compute
\series default 
: 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\Omega=\left(\partial_{t}\ln a\right)\textrm{d}t$
\end_inset 

, 
\series bold 
denote
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $b(t)\equiv\partial_{t}\ln a=\partial_{\tilde{t}}\tilde{a}$
\end_inset 

; 
\series bold 
then
\series default 
 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{d}\Omega=b\textrm{d}t$
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}\approx\left(1-2\Phi\right)b\partial_{t}$
\end_inset 

; 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\mathbf{w}\right|^{2}\approx\left(1-2\Phi\right)b^{2}$
\end_inset 

 to first order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset 

.
\newline 
